rope":"Normandie, Europe"},"cs":{"Abt 1165–":"okolo 1165–Zesnulý","1165–Male":"1165–Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","1190–Male":"1190–Zesnulý","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–1245":"–1245","–Male":"Zesnulý","1190":"1190","about 1209":"okolo 1209","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"okolo 1165","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"od srpen 1189 do 1219","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe"},"da":{"Abt 1165–":"omkring 1165–Afdød","1165–Male":"1165–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1190–Male":"1190–Afdød","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–1245":"–1245","–Male":"Afdød","1190":"1190","about 1209":"omkring 1209","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"omkring 1165","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"fra august 1189 til 1219","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe"},"nl":{"Abt 1165–":"circa 1165–Overleden","1165–Male":"1165–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1190–Male":"1190–Overleden","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–1245":"–1245","–Male":"Overleden","1190":"1190","about 1209":"circa 1209","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"circa 1165","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"van augustus 1189 to 1219","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europa"},"en":{"Abt 1165–":"about 1165–Deceased","1165–Male":"1165–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–1245":"–1245","–Male":"Deceased","1190":"1190","about 1209":"about 1209","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"about 1165","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"from August 1189 to 1219","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marshall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marchel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jacek, Ryszard.  German Ernst.","Polish: probably from French <i>maréchal</i> or Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>, which was originally an occupational name for someone who was in charge of the horses of a household, later a military rank for a senior general. See   Marshall   and compare   Marszalek  ."]},{"name":"Mercier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Gaston, Lucien, Aurele, Jacques, Normand, Laurent, Michel, Valmont.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): occupational name for a merchant, from Old French <i>mercier</i>, from Late Latin <i>merciarius</i> (an agent derivative of <i>merx</i>, genitive <i>mercis</i> ‘merchandise’). This name was also taken to England by Huguenot refugees. Compare   Marshall   and   Mercy  ."]},{"name":"Maniscalco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Vito, Sal, Antonio, Ignazio, Carmelo, Francesco, Gaspare, Saverio, Antonino, Carlo, Damiano.","Italian (southern): occupational name from <i>maniscalco</i> ‘farrier’, altered from <i>marescalco</i> by folk etymology, probably influenced by <i>mano</i> ‘hand’, from medieval Latin <i>mariscalcus</i>, <i>marescalcus</i>. Compare   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marchal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Jacques, Maryse, Philippe, Pierre, Veronique.","French and Walloon: status name or occupational name from Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The term is of ancient Germanic origin (from <i>marah</i> ‘horse, mare’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’) and was originally applied to a man who looked after horses. In the Middle Ages it also came to be used on the one hand as an occupational name for a farrier, and on the other as a status name for an officer of state, in particular a member of a royal household with military responsibilities. Compare English   Marshall   and 2 below.","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in Glamorgan, Wales."]},{"name":"Maskell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  , derived from Middle English, Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The first element in the placename Mascallsbury (Essex) derives from the surname of a 13th-century individual named Robert <i>le Marescal</i>."]},{"name":"Marszalek","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Piotr, Alicja, Andrzej, Eugeniusz, Henryk, Jerzy, Kazimierz, Mieczyslaw, Wieslaw, Zbigniew, Zofia, Zygmunt.","Polish (<b>Marszałek</b>): occupational or status name from the vocabulary word <i>marszałek</i> ‘marshal’, denoting anything from a high court official, a field marshal, or the chairman of the Polish parliament, to the senior servant in a great household. Compare English   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marshell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marschall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hedwig, Juergen, Reinhard, Theresia, Wilfried.","German: occupational name for a man in the service of a member of the nobility, originally one who looked after the horses, Middle High German <i>marschalc</i> (from <i>mar(c)</i> ‘noble horse’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant’). In time the term came to be used for a military rank or a certain court official. Compare   Marshall  .","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marshal","meanings":["(1997: 186;2007: 634; 2010: NA)","English and Scottish: variant of   Marshall  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Marshall was born about 1165 as the son of John Fitz Gilbert. He married Countess Of Pembroke Isabel De Clare from August 1189 to 1219. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 5 daughters."},"et":{"Abt 1165–":"umbes 1165–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–1245":"–1245","–Male":"Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1209":"umbes 1209","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"august 1189 kuni 1219","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe"},"fi":{"Abt 1165–":"noin 1165–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–1245":"–1245","–Male":"Kuollut","1190":"1190","about 1209":"noin 1209","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"noin 1165","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"vuodesta elokuu 1189 vuoteen 1219","Normandie, 